1
00:00:04,050 --> 00:00:07,451
First of all, I'd like to remind you

2
00:00:07,651 --> 00:00:10,432
to turn your cell phones into silent mode.

3
00:00:11,632 --> 00:00:16,053
And by the way, this is my second talk here at GDC,

4
00:00:17,054 --> 00:00:20,115
and it is completely the same as the first one,

5
00:00:20,155 --> 00:00:22,195
so you may have probably heard this one.

6
00:00:24,436 --> 00:00:25,996
Okay, now let's start.

7
00:00:28,009 --> 00:00:34,298
My name is Vladimir. I am from Russian game development studio Picsonic and

8
00:00:34,318 --> 00:00:36,400
I have about seven years of

9
00:00:37,242 --> 00:00:41,567
mobile experience and games for social networks and

10
00:00:41,587 --> 00:00:43,009
I'd like to share with you

11
00:00:44,757 --> 00:00:48,698
my experience of answering specific questions at Pixonic.

12
00:00:49,778 --> 00:00:52,239
And actually, I think that these questions

13
00:00:52,639 --> 00:00:54,019
bother every game studio,

14
00:00:54,519 --> 00:00:56,100
no matter what games you're working on,

15
00:00:56,140 --> 00:00:57,640
what platform or what genre.

16
00:00:58,441 --> 00:01:00,321
Still, you have to answer them,

17
00:01:00,981 --> 00:01:02,442
and they are as follows.

18
00:01:02,682 --> 00:01:04,862
Okay, we've got some revenue flow now.

19
00:01:06,003 --> 00:01:07,823
How exactly are we going to keep it?

20
00:01:08,263 --> 00:01:09,884
Or how are we going to increase it?

21
00:01:10,044 --> 00:01:10,824
What should we do next?

22
00:01:11,905 --> 00:01:14,345
How to grow, to make your game grow?

23
00:01:16,183 --> 00:01:20,507
So, I understand that answering these questions could,

24
00:01:20,867 --> 00:01:23,390
the answers to these questions could vary greatly

25
00:01:23,530 --> 00:01:25,752
depending on your field of expertise,

26
00:01:26,473 --> 00:01:28,855
on the market background, history of the company,

27
00:01:28,895 --> 00:01:31,878
and all that stuff, and this is just my version.

28
00:01:33,459 --> 00:01:36,722
First of all, let me tell you a bit about our context.

29
00:01:36,822 --> 00:01:37,683
Where are we here?

30
00:01:39,580 --> 00:01:47,104
We are situated in Moscow and we've been making games since 2009 and War Robots is our biggest

31
00:01:47,184 --> 00:01:48,104
hit so far.

32
00:01:48,665 --> 00:01:55,048
It is a mobile shooter PvP game where players pilot giant robots fighting each other with

33
00:01:55,228 --> 00:02:00,650
various weapons like missiles, lasers, cannons, machine guns, all that stuff.

34
00:02:02,237 --> 00:02:04,938
And the game was released in 2014.

35
00:02:06,119 --> 00:02:07,620
It is pretty popular right now.

36
00:02:07,900 --> 00:02:11,362
By the way, this slide is outdated a bit.

37
00:02:11,862 --> 00:02:14,544
Now we have more than 120 million installs

38
00:02:14,564 --> 00:02:15,344
on all the platforms.

39
00:02:16,145 --> 00:02:18,946
And about 1.5 million of players pilot robots

40
00:02:18,966 --> 00:02:19,947
in our game every day.

41
00:02:22,489 --> 00:02:24,730
Why the game became popular in the beginning?

42
00:02:25,130 --> 00:02:27,271
Why it became successful?

43
00:02:28,171 --> 00:02:30,592
I think that at the time when it was released,

44
00:02:30,672 --> 00:02:32,993
there were very few mobile shooters on the market

45
00:02:33,213 --> 00:02:36,395
and players actually wanted to play mobile shooters.

46
00:02:38,932 --> 00:02:40,232
they had little choice.

47
00:02:40,892 --> 00:02:43,473
The game wasn't very good at the time.

48
00:02:43,493 --> 00:02:46,494
There were a lot of flaws and the metrics weren't good,

49
00:02:46,894 --> 00:02:50,915
but still, we had our community growing.

50
00:02:51,295 --> 00:02:54,596
We had our Facebook groups growing.

51
00:02:55,556 --> 00:02:58,357
The word of mouth about the game, it was spreading.

52
00:02:59,557 --> 00:03:03,218
And we had to answer these questions,

53
00:03:03,298 --> 00:03:04,338
I said it in the beginning,

54
00:03:05,178 --> 00:03:07,759
that how exactly are we going to grow?

55
00:03:09,307 --> 00:03:10,948
We are mobile and we are free to play.

56
00:03:12,168 --> 00:03:13,489
And we are game developers, right?

57
00:03:13,649 --> 00:03:15,790
So we wanted to add new features to the game.

58
00:03:15,870 --> 00:03:17,390
But what features exactly?

59
00:03:18,451 --> 00:03:20,332
And for the sake of my argument here,

60
00:03:21,632 --> 00:03:24,593
I'll talk about two models, two approaches.

61
00:03:24,853 --> 00:03:26,494
There could be different classifications

62
00:03:26,674 --> 00:03:30,475
or there are a lot of ways to classify features.

63
00:03:30,595 --> 00:03:30,796
But...

64
00:03:31,974 --> 00:03:34,815
I like to talk about the hype model, as I call it,

65
00:03:35,575 --> 00:03:38,697
and it is characterized by a high spike of revenue

66
00:03:38,777 --> 00:03:40,337
in the beginning when it is released,

67
00:03:41,198 --> 00:03:42,838
and a quick drop down afterwards.

68
00:03:43,379 --> 00:03:47,100
Usually, most of the content in the game released

69
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:48,541
behaves like this.

70
00:03:49,501 --> 00:03:52,802
The second model, it is what I call value growth model,

71
00:03:53,562 --> 00:03:57,824
and it is all about sacrificing short-term gain

72
00:03:57,964 --> 00:03:59,545
for long-term profit.

73
00:04:02,081 --> 00:04:06,306
It could be difficult to understand if this feature is successful from the beginning

74
00:04:06,326 --> 00:04:08,609
because you don't have a high revenue spike from the start,

75
00:04:09,310 --> 00:04:14,176
but it will definitely bring you money afterwards.

76
00:04:15,568 --> 00:04:18,769
Basically value growth model, it is a bit trickier

77
00:04:18,809 --> 00:04:20,370
to design this kind of features

78
00:04:20,730 --> 00:04:23,891
because it is about designing needs

79
00:04:24,131 --> 00:04:26,412
that are impossible to fulfill in the game.

80
00:04:26,652 --> 00:04:28,032
They should be continuous.

81
00:04:28,812 --> 00:04:31,433
And it is like the very basic human needs

82
00:04:31,533 --> 00:04:35,434
like the need for food, for sleep, for sex, all that stuff.

83
00:04:36,474 --> 00:04:40,536
So, hype model I think it is a bit easier to design

84
00:04:40,676 --> 00:04:43,757
and to analyze if it is successful or not after the release.

85
00:04:46,123 --> 00:04:47,944
which one of these models is better.

86
00:04:49,565 --> 00:04:50,425
I don't know, frankly.

87
00:04:51,585 --> 00:04:56,448
And there are advantages and disadvantages

88
00:04:56,608 --> 00:04:57,628
of both approaches.

89
00:04:58,449 --> 00:05:01,490
But first of all, what you should understand

90
00:05:01,570 --> 00:05:04,452
that it should correspond with your goals.

91
00:05:05,172 --> 00:05:09,794
If exactly you want to get returns fast,

92
00:05:10,254 --> 00:05:12,676
in this case, you probably should use the hype model.

93
00:05:13,885 --> 00:05:17,626
as a methodology for the designing of your feature.

94
00:05:18,167 --> 00:05:20,308
And if you're going to,

95
00:05:21,348 --> 00:05:23,469
if you're ready to wait to get more money,

96
00:05:23,789 --> 00:05:26,290
in this case, value growth is much better for you.

97
00:05:27,971 --> 00:05:30,792
Basically, it is like a marshmallow test

98
00:05:31,952 --> 00:05:34,674
offered to kids when you have just one marshmallow

99
00:05:34,734 --> 00:05:35,314
and you can eat it,

100
00:05:36,114 --> 00:05:38,275
or you can wait to get the second marshmallow.

101
00:05:39,576 --> 00:05:42,977
And in 2015, when we thought about it,

102
00:05:43,597 --> 00:05:45,557
we actually failed that test.

103
00:05:46,018 --> 00:05:48,418
We ate our marshmallow and we wanted to grow quickly

104
00:05:48,458 --> 00:05:50,759
because we needed money for user acquisition.

105
00:05:50,819 --> 00:05:53,839
We wanted our marketing budget to grow quickly.

106
00:05:55,340 --> 00:06:00,401
Now let's try to compare the examples of features

107
00:06:00,561 --> 00:06:01,921
for each kind of model.

108
00:06:02,501 --> 00:06:04,102
And the example of the hype model

109
00:06:04,722 --> 00:06:07,162
which was made in War Robots is Gacha.

110
00:06:10,059 --> 00:06:14,864
Basically, gacha is like a chocolate egg with a toy,

111
00:06:15,024 --> 00:06:17,227
or here you may know it as a kinder joy.

112
00:06:18,088 --> 00:06:20,971
You have a random reward inside the egg,

113
00:06:21,852 --> 00:06:23,914
but even if you don't like this reward,

114
00:06:24,094 --> 00:06:25,376
you still have the chocolate.

115
00:06:26,857 --> 00:06:28,119
And it is useful for you.

116
00:06:28,259 --> 00:06:32,543
Every chocolate egg you buy, it is still useful to you.

117
00:06:34,106 --> 00:06:37,667
The third principle you can use,

118
00:06:38,027 --> 00:06:40,648
that actually real toy manufacturers

119
00:06:40,688 --> 00:06:42,449
can't use this principle, but we can,

120
00:06:42,969 --> 00:06:45,250
it is creating illusion of randomness

121
00:06:45,390 --> 00:06:46,630
instead of real randomness.

122
00:06:47,230 --> 00:06:50,872
What I mean is, imagine that you are throwing

123
00:06:50,892 --> 00:06:53,873
a pair of dices and you get snake eyes

124
00:06:54,273 --> 00:06:55,213
five times in a row.

125
00:06:56,814 --> 00:06:58,954
This is how real randomness works.

126
00:06:59,959 --> 00:07:03,101
It doesn't have to be fair, but we humans are upset with it,

127
00:07:03,501 --> 00:07:05,582
and we perceive this as something unfair.

128
00:07:05,622 --> 00:07:06,783
We want it to be regular.

129
00:07:07,604 --> 00:07:10,425
That is why, if you are designing the experience

130
00:07:10,485 --> 00:07:12,447
of players using random mechanics,

131
00:07:12,547 --> 00:07:14,328
if you're creating an illusion of randomness,

132
00:07:14,608 --> 00:07:16,349
but it is regular all the time,

133
00:07:16,850 --> 00:07:18,611
it will be much better for you

134
00:07:20,092 --> 00:07:21,753
and for players in your game.

135
00:07:23,910 --> 00:07:28,214
So we started releasing Gacha.

136
00:07:28,274 --> 00:07:30,756
The first one was on Halloween 2016

137
00:07:30,796 --> 00:07:32,197
and it was a part of the event.

138
00:07:32,798 --> 00:07:35,580
At the time we had just one type of chests

139
00:07:36,401 --> 00:07:40,564
and players played battles,

140
00:07:41,204 --> 00:07:43,907
earned special event currency called pumpkins,

141
00:07:44,047 --> 00:07:46,188
and opened the chests with rewards.

142
00:07:47,109 --> 00:07:48,771
There were different rewards inside it,

143
00:07:48,891 --> 00:07:50,952
robots, weapons, currencies.

144
00:07:52,267 --> 00:07:55,329
And the only UX feature we've added at the time

145
00:07:55,669 --> 00:07:59,533
was that you could open multiple chests with just one tap.

146
00:07:59,613 --> 00:08:00,533
That's all that we did.

147
00:08:02,115 --> 00:08:06,338
We introduced it on the event just to have an insurance.

148
00:08:06,598 --> 00:08:10,421
If players didn't like this, then the event would be over

149
00:08:10,601 --> 00:08:12,303
and the game returned to its previous state.

150
00:08:12,623 --> 00:08:14,064
But it was successful for us,

151
00:08:14,564 --> 00:08:15,906
and this is why we continued.

152
00:08:16,286 --> 00:08:18,408
We made a second iteration on the New Year 17.

153
00:08:19,669 --> 00:08:23,752
when we've added our version of the chocolate

154
00:08:24,192 --> 00:08:28,775
in the Kinder Joy, which is when you are opening

155
00:08:28,935 --> 00:08:33,659
every chest, a special progress bar fills a little.

156
00:08:34,780 --> 00:08:37,582
And when it is filled completely,

157
00:08:37,942 --> 00:08:40,884
player gets super reward that is useful

158
00:08:40,944 --> 00:08:42,065
to everyone in the game.

159
00:08:43,497 --> 00:08:44,338
That's how it works.

160
00:08:44,458 --> 00:08:49,620
That's how works the fact that every opening of the chest,

161
00:08:50,060 --> 00:08:52,262
no matter what will you receive inside,

162
00:08:53,422 --> 00:08:54,543
will be useful to you.

163
00:08:56,063 --> 00:08:59,525
The third iteration was on Lunar New Year 17

164
00:09:00,065 --> 00:09:01,606
and we've added two more chests

165
00:09:01,886 --> 00:09:04,168
to address the needs of our game community.

166
00:09:04,508 --> 00:09:06,749
Some players actually wanted these chests

167
00:09:06,769 --> 00:09:10,331
to be a bit cheaper and some players wanted

168
00:09:11,151 --> 00:09:14,112
the rewards to be better, and we've added premium chests

169
00:09:15,092 --> 00:09:20,174
with a higher price, and cheap chests with lower price,

170
00:09:20,234 --> 00:09:22,895
just so that you could play it as a lottery.

171
00:09:23,796 --> 00:09:26,017
And actually, this was the first time

172
00:09:26,097 --> 00:09:27,757
when our game community signaled

173
00:09:28,258 --> 00:09:30,778
that they don't like how exactly

174
00:09:32,159 --> 00:09:33,780
we are designing our monetization,

175
00:09:33,940 --> 00:09:35,840
where the game is moved.

176
00:09:36,761 --> 00:09:36,921
And

177
00:09:38,348 --> 00:09:39,993
This wasn't a problem for us at the time

178
00:09:40,013 --> 00:09:41,298
because the metrics were good,

179
00:09:41,759 --> 00:09:44,850
there were no problems at all, and we just continued.

180
00:09:47,047 --> 00:09:50,010
The fourth iteration was on War Robots Birthday,

181
00:09:50,491 --> 00:09:55,375
and we tried to avoid adding new event currencies.

182
00:09:55,896 --> 00:09:59,679
And from now on, the chests were opened with hard currency,

183
00:09:59,719 --> 00:10:01,301
with usual hard currency of the game.

184
00:10:01,761 --> 00:10:03,283
In this way, we've created a loop

185
00:10:03,723 --> 00:10:06,986
where a player opens the chest, gets the hard currency,

186
00:10:07,426 --> 00:10:10,309
and they can use it to open the next chest.

187
00:10:11,010 --> 00:10:13,490
But this wasn't a successful thing for us

188
00:10:13,970 --> 00:10:17,431
because players' feedback was that

189
00:10:18,712 --> 00:10:22,053
in-game hard currency was too valuable for them.

190
00:10:22,133 --> 00:10:24,633
They didn't want to spend it on opening the chests.

191
00:10:25,353 --> 00:10:28,134
That is why we returned to the previous state,

192
00:10:28,234 --> 00:10:33,275
but we recreated loops with our event currencies

193
00:10:34,456 --> 00:10:35,236
on the 4th of July.

194
00:10:36,296 --> 00:10:39,997
Now, why we experimented with this feature so many times?

195
00:10:40,097 --> 00:10:42,198
Why we did it in so many iterations?

196
00:10:43,098 --> 00:10:45,999
The answer is actually on this chart.

197
00:10:46,099 --> 00:10:47,179
It is our revenue chart.

198
00:10:47,279 --> 00:10:49,920
And you can see that every time we've added

199
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:56,581
gacha to our events, every time it was a spike in the revenue.

200
00:10:57,637 --> 00:11:00,457
That is why we understood that we actually want to add

201
00:11:01,037 --> 00:11:03,658
this mechanics to the game permanently.

202
00:11:04,318 --> 00:11:07,659
And we did it in September 2017.

203
00:11:08,259 --> 00:11:09,259
It was designed as follows.

204
00:11:09,499 --> 00:11:11,240
There were three special currencies,

205
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:13,380
key cards, red, green, and blue.

206
00:11:14,240 --> 00:11:16,741
And they represented time-limited seasons.

207
00:11:17,261 --> 00:11:19,342
So that when one season ends,

208
00:11:19,842 --> 00:11:23,002
and for instance, you get compensations for red key cards

209
00:11:23,723 --> 00:11:27,243
in different currencies or other types of rewards.

210
00:11:28,484 --> 00:11:33,409
And now we have to use green key cards to open chests.

211
00:11:33,970 --> 00:11:36,633
In this way, we actually prevented key cards

212
00:11:36,713 --> 00:11:38,875
from stacking up on players' accounts.

213
00:11:42,305 --> 00:11:44,166
This was a very successful feature for us.

214
00:11:45,307 --> 00:11:48,509
Actually, I might say that this was the most successful

215
00:11:48,569 --> 00:11:50,751
feature for our robots in terms of financial games

216
00:11:50,791 --> 00:11:53,013
because we had two or three times increase

217
00:11:53,053 --> 00:11:54,193
of our revenue at the time,

218
00:11:54,734 --> 00:11:56,555
and we thought that it is a new plateau

219
00:11:56,575 --> 00:11:57,576
for our robots actually.

220
00:12:01,403 --> 00:12:04,986
We now had the fuel to continue our experiments

221
00:12:05,426 --> 00:12:08,209
with monetization and we've added more features

222
00:12:08,309 --> 00:12:11,972
like wild offer system, I'll talk about it later,

223
00:12:12,732 --> 00:12:16,355
and the other versions of indirect sale system

224
00:12:16,375 --> 00:12:20,118
because basically what gacha is in our game,

225
00:12:20,339 --> 00:12:23,301
it is a way to sell your

226
00:12:23,942 --> 00:12:30,383
content indirectly to players, to hide the real price of this unit, because player

227
00:12:30,863 --> 00:12:36,204
doesn't know how many chests they have to open to get this unit.

228
00:12:37,965 --> 00:12:39,365
And we've added component system.

229
00:12:41,466 --> 00:12:47,747
It was our way to sell half of the robot. From that point you could

230
00:12:48,227 --> 00:12:53,768
offer players 5,000 components when, for instance, they need 10,000 to craft a robot.

231
00:12:57,012 --> 00:13:02,356
But the market changed, and there was a big media scandal

232
00:13:02,376 --> 00:13:03,897
around Star Wars Battlefront II,

233
00:13:04,257 --> 00:13:06,878
and I remember that some players even joked about it,

234
00:13:07,559 --> 00:13:11,001
like, imagine if Darth Vader cost not 40 bucks,

235
00:13:11,181 --> 00:13:15,164
but 300 bucks, implying our the most expensive robot

236
00:13:15,184 --> 00:13:15,644
in the game.

237
00:13:17,417 --> 00:13:21,281
We looked at it, but still game metrics were good.

238
00:13:21,361 --> 00:13:23,403
There weren't any problems on the game metrics.

239
00:13:23,483 --> 00:13:26,746
The retention was fine, the conversion rates,

240
00:13:26,906 --> 00:13:28,587
monetization, everything was good.

241
00:13:28,968 --> 00:13:31,530
The only problem was on the iOS rating.

242
00:13:32,010 --> 00:13:35,073
This drop wasn't very big, but it was significant for us.

243
00:13:37,718 --> 00:13:41,602
And we've definitely, we've won in terms of money

244
00:13:41,622 --> 00:13:44,004
with this feature, but we've lost something.

245
00:13:45,005 --> 00:13:47,588
And first of all, players actually reached

246
00:13:48,008 --> 00:13:50,230
every developer they could through social media

247
00:13:50,871 --> 00:13:55,015
and wrote them, you're bad, you suck,

248
00:13:55,656 --> 00:13:57,077
we don't like what you do with the game.

249
00:13:58,598 --> 00:14:02,042
And people started to be ashamed of what they're doing.

250
00:14:03,143 --> 00:14:05,985
It's like, imagine you're working on one of the best

251
00:14:06,065 --> 00:14:07,506
mobile shooters in the world,

252
00:14:08,386 --> 00:14:09,507
and you don't like what you do.

253
00:14:09,607 --> 00:14:11,268
That was a problem for us,

254
00:14:11,368 --> 00:14:13,909
and it turned into

255
00:14:16,490 --> 00:14:17,411
slower production.

256
00:14:17,651 --> 00:14:20,232
The features made after that were made slower

257
00:14:21,032 --> 00:14:24,414
because people were really afraid to get another wave

258
00:14:24,674 --> 00:14:27,316
of hatred from our community.

259
00:14:29,414 --> 00:14:31,917
That was the first time for us when we understood

260
00:14:31,977 --> 00:14:33,558
that we are doing something wrong

261
00:14:33,658 --> 00:14:35,360
